Looks like a rebase onto https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/dbus-sensors/+/60370 should do the trick...
What was your process for determining whether a device's driver exposed hwmon attributes?
Yeah, I would have expected `true` on all of these, since (AFAIK) they're all pmbus devices and hence should provide a hwmon interface.
I went back through the sensors and put true for the drivers I found references to in the hwmon folder.

Okay, that sounds like a reasonable approach, but it looks like something didn't go quite right in applying it -- for example:

```
$ git grep -i ir38164 drivers/hwmon/
drivers/hwmon/pmbus/Kconfig:      IR38060, IR38064, IR38164 and IR38263.
drivers/hwmon/pmbus/ir38064.c:  {"ir38164", 0},
drivers/hwmon/pmbus/ir38064.c:  { .compatible = "infineon,ir38164" },
```

It'd be good to verify, but I'm pretty sure these should all be `true`.
Hmm yeah I think the sources I was looking at are out of date.  I moved everything to true.
May want to match here https://github.com/openbmc/entity-manager/blob/master/include/devices.hpp
All types seem to match except ADM sensor, but those do show up as hwmon dirs (at least from what I've seen).
What do you mean here? The sensor type map key vs the I2CDeviceType driver name? Something else?

> The sensor type map key vs the I2CDeviceType driver name?

Yeah, basically that I think -- see https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/dbus-sensors/+/59761/comment/80a5b314_dadbb232/
We can't search with case insensitivity? Not that it really matters if we do a linear scan given the number of entries, just it seems silly to be tripped up by case differences.
I added a comparator to the flat map that'll achieve case insensitive compare.
This patch should have the meson.build change in https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/dbus-sensors/+/59761
Added
why this change?

After looking at it, since it's not really needed I reverted back to the original assignment.  One change I decided to make was switching sensorType to be a string.  Since that's what the PSUSensor constructor is looking for it makes sense imo.
Why is this change needed?
This was added to fix this issue - https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/dbus-sensors/+/60368/5..18/src/PSUSensorMain.cpp#b310
What if another device type like I3CDevice comes in future?
It depends what the attributes would look like, but the structures seem pretty malleable. I think we should make those changes when we get an I3C device though.
why we cant directly compare the string return (a==b)
Using == should work too, but I opted for this way since it should be faster.
